Use `.filter()` to create a new array without the unwanted item, then assign it back to the `@tracked` property. `.filter()` returns a new array reference, which triggers Glimmer's reactivity. Never use `.splice()` on a `@tracked` array — it mutates in place and won't re-render.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreEditorComponent extends Component {
  @tracked innings = [
    { batsman: 'Tamim', runs: 45 },
    { batsman: 'Liton', runs: 32 },
    { batsman: 'Shakib', runs: 78 },
  ];

  @action
  updateRuns(batsmanName, newRuns) {
    this.innings = this.innings.map(entry =>
      entry.batsman === batsmanName ? { ...entry, runs: newRuns } : entry
    );
  }

  <template>
    {{#each this.innings as |entry|}}
      <p>{{entry.batsman}}: {{entry.runs}}</p>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
Use `.map()` to iterate and return a new array where the target item is replaced with a new object (spread the old item and override changed fields). Both `.map()` and the object spread ensure immutability, which is required for Glimmer to detect the change.

