The `filteredPlayers` getter reads both `this.query` and `this.allPlayers`, so it automatically re-runs when either changes. Computing the filtered list in a getter is preferred over storing it in a separate `@tracked` array, which would require manual synchronization.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class TopScorersComponent extends Component {
  @tracked players = [
    { name: 'Shakib', runs: 4500 },
    { name: 'Tamim', runs: 8000 },
    { name: 'Mushfiq', runs: 5200 },
    { name: 'Mahmudullah', runs: 4100 },
  ];
  @tracked sortDir = 'desc';

  get sortedPlayers() {
    return [...this.players].sort((a, b) =>
      this.sortDir === 'desc' ? b.runs - a.runs : a.runs - b.runs
    );
  }

  @action
  toggleSort() {
    this.sortDir = this.sortDir === 'desc' ? 'asc' : 'desc';
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.toggleSort}}>Sort {{this.sortDir}}</button>
    {{#each this.sortedPlayers as |player|}}
      <p>{{player.name}}: {{player.runs}}</p>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
Always spread the array before sorting: `[...this.players].sort(...)`. The native `.sort()` mutates in place — if you called it directly on `this.players`, you'd mutate the tracked array without triggering reactivity. Spreading creates a new array that `.sort()` can safely mutate.

