Native `Set` is not tracked by Glimmer, so the workaround is to store ids in a `@tracked` array and derive a `Set` in a getter for O(1) lookup. The getter re-runs whenever `pinnedIds` changes, giving both reactivity and fast `.has()` checks in the template.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class PinControls extends Component {
  @tracked pinnedIds = [];

  @action
  pinPlayer(playerId) {
    if (this.pinnedIds.includes(playerId)) return;
    this.pinnedIds = [...this.pinnedIds, playerId];
  }

  @action
  unpinPlayer(playerId) {
    this.pinnedIds = this.pinnedIds.filter(id => id !== playerId);
  }

  @action
  togglePin(playerId) {
    if (this.pinnedIds.includes(playerId)) {
      this.unpinPlayer(playerId);
    } else {
      this.pinPlayer(playerId);
    }
  }

  <template>
    {{#each @players as |player|}}
      <button
        type="button"
        {{on "click" (fn this.togglePin player.id)}}
        class="px-2 py-1 text-xs rounded {{if (this.pinnedIds.includes player.id) 'bg-yellow-400' 'bg-gray-200'}}"
      >
        {{player.name}}
      </button>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
`pinPlayer` guards against duplicates with `.includes()` before spreading. `unpinPlayer` creates a new filtered array. The `togglePin` action composes both for a single-click toggle pattern. All three create new array references to satisfy Glimmer's reactivity.

