```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class AutotrackingDemo extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;

  // Glimmer tracks which @tracked values this getter READS
  get matchSummary() {
    // During evaluation, autotracking records: 'score' and 'wickets' were accessed
    return `${this.score}/${this.wickets}`;
  }

  <template>
    {{!-- Template also participates in tracking when rendered --}}
    <p>{{this.matchSummary}}</p>
    <p>Score: {{this.score}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer uses a global "tracking frame" that is active whenever a getter or template renders. Any `@tracked` property that is *read* during that frame is automatically registered as a dependency. When any registered dependency is later written to, Glimmer marks the consumer (getter or template expression) as invalid and schedules a re-render. This happens without any manual subscription or `connect` call — it is entirely implicit and happens at read time.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ReRenderExplainer extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;

  @action
  addRun() {
    // Step 1: this.runs is written
    // Step 2: Glimmer marks all consumers that READ this.runs as dirty
    // Step 3: On next microtask tick, dirty consumers re-render
    this.runs = this.runs + 1;
  }

  <template>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+1 Run</button>
    <p>{{this.runs}}</p> {{!-- This expression read 'runs', so it re-renders --}}
  </template>
}
```
Each `@tracked` property has an internal revision tag — a monotonically incrementing counter. When you assign a new value, the tag's revision increments. Glimmer's rendering system checks these revision numbers before re-rendering a template expression. If a tag's revision is higher than when the expression last rendered, Glimmer knows the output may have changed and re-evaluates it. The re-render is batched and asynchronous — scheduled as a microtask — so multiple synchronous writes in one action only produce one render cycle.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class NoReRenderExample extends Component {
  // Plain property — NOT reactive
  playerName = 'Tamim Iqbal';

  @action
  changeName() {
    // This assignment happens, but Glimmer has no revision tag for it
    // so no consumers are marked dirty — no re-render occurs
    this.playerName = 'Shakib Al Hasan';
  }

  <template>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.changeName}}>Change Player</button>
    {{!-- This will always show 'Tamim Iqbal' no matter how many times you click --}}
    <p>{{this.playerName}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
A plain class property has no revision tag. When Glimmer's autotracking system evaluates the template and reads `this.playerName`, it finds no tag to register. Therefore, writing to `this.playerName` later has no associated tag to increment, and no consumers are marked dirty. The template never re-renders. Plain properties are still valid for values that genuinely do not change the UI — like a DOM element reference or a timer id — but any value that drives template output must be decorated with `@tracked`.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class GetterTracking extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 40;
  @tracked balls = 30;

  // This getter does NOT have its own tag.
  // It is memoized: re-evaluated only when its dependencies change.
  get strikeRate() {
    // Autotracking records: 'runs' and 'balls' were read
    return ((this.runs / this.balls) * 100).toFixed(1);
  }

  <template>
    <p>Strike Rate: {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Getters do not have their own revision tags; instead they act as *consumers* of the tags of the tracked properties they read. Glimmer memoizes the getter's result: after the first evaluation it caches the output. On subsequent reads, Glimmer checks whether any tracked property read during the last evaluation has a newer revision. If none have changed, the cached result is returned without re-running the getter body. If any dependency changed, the getter re-runs. This means getters are "lazily invalidated" — they only re-compute when actually needed by a template or another getter.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class GetterNoTracked extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 50;
  @tracked wickets = 2;

  // No @tracked needed — getter is automatically reactive
  // because it reads @tracked 'runs' and 'wickets'
  get scoreDisplay() {
    return `${this.runs}/${this.wickets}`;
  }

  // WRONG — @tracked on a getter is a syntax error
  // @tracked get scoreDisplay() { ... } // ❌ Do not do this

  <template>
    <p class="text-xl font-bold">{{this.scoreDisplay}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
`@tracked` is a decorator for *storage* — it instruments a class field with a revision tag. A getter has no storage of its own; it is a computed function. Its reactivity comes entirely from the tracked properties it reads during evaluation. Applying `@tracked` to a getter is a conceptual error and would throw a runtime error. If you want to memoize an expensive getter, use `@cached` (from `@glimmer/tracking`) instead.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ChainedGetters extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 45;
  @tracked balls = 30;

  // Layer 1: reads @tracked directly
  get strikeRate() {
    return (this.runs / this.balls) * 100;
  }

  // Layer 2: reads getter A
  get performanceGrade() {
    // When 'runs' changes:
    //   1. strikeRate is marked dirty
    //   2. performanceGrade is marked dirty (because it read strikeRate)
    //   3. gradeWithLabel is marked dirty
    if (this.strikeRate >= 150) return 'A';
    if (this.strikeRate >= 100) return 'B';
    return 'C';
  }

  // Layer 3: reads getter B
  get gradeWithLabel() {
    return `Grade: ${this.performanceGrade} (SR: ${this.strikeRate.toFixed(1)})`;
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.gradeWithLabel}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Invalidation propagates lazily through the chain. When `runs` changes, Glimmer marks `strikeRate` dirty. When `strikeRate` is then read (by `performanceGrade` during re-render), it re-computes and Glimmer records that `performanceGrade` now depends on the new `strikeRate` result. Each layer only re-computes once per render cycle, regardless of how many consumers it has.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ActionBinding extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;

  // Without @action: when the browser calls this as an event handler,
  // 'this' is undefined (strict mode) or the event target (sloppy mode)
  brokenIncrement() {
    this.score += 1; // TypeError: Cannot set property 'score' of undefined
  }

  // With @action: 'this' is always bound to the component instance
  @action
  increment() {
    this.score += 1; // Works correctly
  }

  <template>
    {{!-- When the browser fires 'click', it calls the function directly
         without the component instance as context --}}
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.increment}}>+1 Run</button>
  </template>
}
```
In JavaScript, when you pass `this.increment` as a callback, you are passing a function reference — the `this` context is lost. `@action` uses `bind(this)` under the hood so that no matter how the function is later invoked, `this` always refers to the component instance. This is why every method you pass to `{{on}}` or as a callback arg should be decorated with `@action`.

