  // No @action needed for the 'this' binding problem
  addWicket = () => {
    this.wickets += 1;
  };

  <template>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addWicket}}>+1 Wicket</button>
    <p>Wickets: {{this.wickets}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Arrow function class fields capture `this` lexically in the class body during construction. Unlike regular methods, they carry their `this` binding with them and do not need `@action` to fix it. However, each instance gets its own function object, which has a minor memory overhead compared to `@action` methods that live on the prototype. For most cases either pattern is fine, but `@action` is the Ember community convention and is slightly more memory-efficient for components with many instances.

```gjs
// GLIMMER approach
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class GlimmerScore extends Component {
  // @tracked is a class property decorator — state lives on the instance
  @tracked runs = 0;

  @action
  addRun() {
    // Direct assignment — no setter function needed
    this.runs += 1;
  }

  <template>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addRun}}>Add Run</button>
    <p>Runs: {{this.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}

// React EQUIVALENT (for comparison — not valid in Ember):
// function ScoreCard() {
//   const [runs, setRuns] = useState(0);
//   // Must use the setter function to trigger re-render
//   return <button onClick={() => setRuns(r => r + 1)}>Add Run</button>;
// }
```
In React, `useState` returns a tuple `[value, setter]` — you *must* call the setter to trigger a re-render. Direct mutation of the variable does nothing. In Glimmer, `@tracked` transforms the property into a get/set pair behind the scenes: *any assignment* to the property (via `this.runs = ...`) is enough to mark consumers dirty. This means Glimmer state reads and writes feel like normal JavaScript properties, while React state requires explicit setter calls.

```gjs
// GLIMMER — @tracked on a class property
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class GlimmerDemo extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;          // Primitive — like Vue ref(0)
  @tracked player = { name: 'Tamim', runs: 0 }; // Object — must replace to trigger update

  // Access: this.score (no .value unwrap needed)
  // Update: this.score = 1 (plain assignment)

  <template><p>{{this.score}}</p></template>
}

// VUE 3 EQUIVALENT (not valid Ember):
// const score = ref(0)        — score.value to read/write
// const player = reactive({}) — player.name = 'X' triggers update (deep)
```
Vue's `ref()` wraps primitives in an object and requires `.value` to access them. Glimmer's `@tracked` is a decorator that intercepts property access transparently — no `.value` unwrap. Vue's `reactive()` makes objects deeply reactive using a Proxy, so nested mutations trigger updates. Glimmer's `@tracked` on an object only tracks the *reference*: you must replace the whole object to trigger re-render. For deep reactivity in Ember, use `TrackedObject` from `tracked-built-ins`.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ArrayMutationBug extends Component {
  @tracked players = ['Tamim', 'Liton'];

  @action
  addPlayerBroken() {
    // ❌ WRONG: push() mutates the existing array IN PLACE
    // The tracked property still points to the SAME array reference
    // Glimmer's revision tag for 'players' did NOT change
    this.players.push('Shakib');
    // Template does NOT re-render
  }

  @action
  addPlayerCorrect() {
    // ✅ CORRECT: spread creates a NEW array reference
    // Assigning to this.players increments its revision tag
    this.players = [...this.players, 'Shakib'];
    // Template re-renders with the new player
  }

  <template>
    <ul>{{#each this.players as |p|}}<li>{{p}}</li>{{/each}}</ul>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addPlayerCorrect}}>Add Player</button>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer tracks the array *reference*, not the array's contents. `push()` mutates the contents without changing the reference, so the revision tag stays at its old value. Glimmer compares the current revision to the last-rendered revision, finds no change, and skips re-rendering. The fix is always to assign a new array (`this.players = [...]`) so the revision tag increments.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ReferenceReplace extends Component {
  @tracked wicketHistory = [];

  @action
  recordWicket(bowlerName) {
    // Step-by-step what happens:
    // 1. [...this.wicketHistory, bowlerName] creates a brand NEW array object
    // 2. Assigning to this.wicketHistory calls the @tracked setter
    // 3. The setter stores the new reference and increments the revision tag
    // 4. Glimmer's rendering queue is notified
    // 5. On next microtask, all template expressions that read 'wicketHistory'
    //    see a newer revision and re-evaluate
    this.wicketHistory = [...this.wicketHistory, bowlerName];
  }

  <template>
    <ul>{{#each this.wicketHistory as |b|}}<li>{{b}}</li>{{/each}}</ul>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" (fn this.recordWicket 'Mustafizur')}}>Record Wicket</button>
  </template>
}
```
The `@tracked` decorator replaces the property with a custom getter/setter pair. The setter stores the new value *and* bumps a revision tag. This tag is the signal Glimmer uses to decide whether to re-run any getter or template expression that previously read this property. A new array reference forces a tag bump; in-place mutation bypasses the setter entirely and never bumps the tag.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { TrackedArray } from 'tracked-built-ins';

export default class TrackedArrayDemo extends Component {
  // TrackedArray wraps native Array with reactive mutation methods
  players = new TrackedArray(['Tamim', 'Liton', 'Shakib']);

  @action
  addPlayer() {
    // push() on a TrackedArray DOES trigger re-render!
    // The TrackedArray overrides mutation methods to bump revision tags
    this.players.push('Mushfiqur');
  }

  @action
  removeFirst() {
    this.players.shift();
  }

  <template>
    <ul>{{#each this.players as |p|}}<li>{{p}}</li>{{/each}}</ul>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addPlayer}}>Add Player</button>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.removeFirst}}>Remove First</button>
  </template>
}
```
A plain `@tracked` array tracks only the reference: mutation methods like `push`, `pop`, and `splice` do not trigger re-renders. `TrackedArray` from `tracked-built-ins` wraps every mutation method (`push`, `pop`, `shift`, `unshift`, `splice`, `sort`, `reverse`, `fill`) to bump an internal revision tag after each mutation. This allows you to mutate the array naturally without creating new array references every time. Note: `TrackedArray` does not need to be decorated with `@tracked` because it manages its own reactivity internally.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ObjectMutationBug extends Component {
  @tracked player = { name: 'Tamim', runs: 0 };

  @action
  addRunsBroken() {
    // ❌ WRONG: this.player still points to the SAME object
    // Only this.player's revision tag is tracked, NOT player.runs's revision
    this.player.runs += 1;
    // The tracked setter for 'player' was never called
    // Revision tag unchanged → no re-render
  }

  @action
  addRunsCorrect() {
    // ✅ CORRECT: creates a new object, calls the tracked setter
    this.player = { ...this.player, runs: this.player.runs + 1 };
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.player.name}}: {{this.player.runs}} runs</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addRunsCorrect}}>Add Run</button>
  </template>
}
```
`@tracked` on `player` instruments the *property access* on the component instance (`this.player`). When you do `this.player.runs = 50`, you are accessing `this.player` (reads the tracked value) and then mutating a nested property on the returned object. This inner mutation never goes through the `@tracked` setter and therefore never bumps the revision tag. Replacing the object via `this.player = { ...this.player, runs: 50 }` calls the setter and bumps the tag.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { TrackedObject } from 'tracked-built-ins';

export default class TrackedObjectDemo extends Component {
  // TrackedObject makes every PROPERTY of the object reactive
  matchStats = new TrackedObject({
    runs: 120,
    wickets: 3,
    overs: 20,
  });

  @action
  addRun() {
    // Direct property mutation NOW triggers re-render!
    this.matchStats.runs += 1;
  }

  @action
  addWicket() {
    this.matchStats.wickets += 1;
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.matchStats.runs}}/{{this.matchStats.wickets}} ({{this.matchStats.overs}} ov)</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+1 Run</button>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addWicket}}>+1 Wicket</button>
  </template>
}
```
Use `TrackedObject` when you have an object whose individual properties change frequently and independently, and you want to avoid spreading on every update. `TrackedObject` uses a Proxy-based approach to instrument each property read and write with its own revision tag. Use a plain `@tracked` object when the object is replaced as a whole (e.g., loading from an API) — the spread pattern is simpler in that case. For form data with many fields updated one at a time, `TrackedObject` is the better choice.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ReadOnlyArgs extends Component {
  // @args.score is passed from parent

  @action
  brokenAttempt() {
    // ❌ WRONG: args are read-only — this will throw an assertion error
    // this.args.score = 100;
  }

  @action
  correctPattern() {
    // ✅ CORRECT: notify parent to change the value
    // The parent holds the @tracked score and updates it
    this.args.onScoreChange?.(100);
  }

  <template>
    <p>Score from parent: {{@score}}</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.correctPattern}}>Update Score</button>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer enforces one-way data flow: data flows down as `@args`, actions flow up as callbacks. `this.args` is a frozen proxy — attempting to write to it throws an assertion error in development. This design prevents "mysterious at a distance" bugs where a child silently changes shared state. Instead, the child calls an `@args.onX` callback to request the parent to update its own `@tracked` state, which then flows back down as a new arg value.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class SetterDemo extends Component {
  @tracked _runs = 0;

  // Setter intercepts assignment, validates, then updates the tracked backing field
  set runs(value) {
    this._runs = Math.max(0, parseInt(value, 10) || 0);
  }

  get runs() {
    return this._runs;
  }

  <template>
    <input
      type="number"
      value={{this.runs}}
      {{on "input" (fn (mut this.runs))}}
      class="border rounded px-2 py-1"
    />
    <p>Validated runs: {{this.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
The setter is a regular JavaScript `set` accessor. Glimmer's reactivity does not care about the setter itself — it cares that the `@tracked` backing field (`_runs`) is written to. When the setter calls `this._runs = ...`, it triggers the `@tracked` setter which bumps the revision tag. The getter `get runs()` then reads `_runs`, registering it as a tracked dependency. This pattern allows validation or transformation logic before the tracked store is updated.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class CleanupDemo extends Component {
  @tracked elapsedSeconds = 0;
  #intervalId = null;

  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args);
    this.#intervalId = setInterval(() => {
      // After component is destroyed, this setter would try to update
      // a tracked property on a destroyed component, causing an assertion error
      this.elapsedSeconds += 1;
    }, 1000);
  }

  willDestroy() {
    super.willDestroy();
    // Clear the interval BEFORE the component is torn down
    clearInterval(this.#intervalId);
    // Now it is safe — no more writes to @tracked after destroy
  }

  <template><p>{{this.elapsedSeconds}}s</p></template>
}
```
Glimmer asserts that you should not modify a component's state after it is destroyed. If a `setInterval` or `addEventListener` keeps a reference to the component and fires after it is removed from the DOM, assigning to `@tracked` properties throws an assertion error in development and silently corrupts state in production. `willDestroy` is the lifecycle hook that runs synchronously before the component's DOM is removed, making it the correct and safe place for all cleanup.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class BatchingDemo extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;
  @tracked overs = 0;

  @action
  endOver(runsInOver) {
    // All three assignments happen synchronously
    // Glimmer does NOT re-render between them
    this.runs += runsInOver;    // tags bumped
    this.wickets += 1;          // tags bumped
    this.overs += 1;            // tags bumped
    // After the @action returns, Glimmer schedules ONE re-render
    // that reflects all three changes simultaneously
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.runs}}/{{this.wickets}} ({{this.overs}} ov)</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" (fn this.endOver 6)}}>End 6-run over</button>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer's rendering is asynchronous — re-renders are scheduled as microtasks, not executed immediately on every assignment. Multiple synchronous writes inside an `@action` only bump revision tags; they do not immediately trigger rendering. After the `@action` synchronous code completes and the call stack unwinds, a single scheduled microtask fires that re-renders the component once, reflecting all changes together. This is why you never see intermediate "partially updated" UI states.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class MixedDependencies extends Component {
  @tracked localBonus = 0;

  // This getter reads:
  //   - this.args.baseRuns (arg dependency)
  //   - this.localBonus (tracked dependency)
  get totalRuns() {
    return (this.args.baseRuns ?? 0) + this.localBonus;
  }

  <template>
    <p>Total: {{this.totalRuns}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
During the getter's first evaluation, Glimmer's tracking frame records *every* reactive source that was read, whether it comes from `@tracked` class properties or from `@args`. Args are also instrumented with revision tags internally. The getter's memoization cache is keyed against the combined set of all dependencies. If the parent re-renders with a new `baseRuns` value, the arg's revision changes and `totalRuns` is invalidated. If `localBonus` is updated locally, its revision changes and `totalRuns` is invalidated again. Either change causes a re-evaluation.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class TemplateTracking extends Component {
  @tracked playerName = 'Tamim';
  @tracked score = 0;

  <template>
    {{!-- Expression A: reads 'playerName' — tracked dependency registered --}}
    <h2>{{this.playerName}}</h2>

    {{!-- Expression B: reads 'score' — separate tracked dependency --}}
    <p class="text-2xl">{{this.score}}</p>

    {{!-- Static content: reads nothing tracked — never re-evaluated --}}
    <footer>Spordium Cricket App</footer>
  </template>
}
```
The Glimmer template compiler compiles each template expression into a "node" with its own tracking frame. When a node is rendered, it registers which tracked values it read. When `score` changes, only the `<p>` node is marked dirty and re-rendered. The `<h2>` node (which only read `playerName`) and the static `<footer>` are unaffected. This fine-grained, expression-level invalidation is why Glimmer is efficient even with large templates — it does not re-render the entire component on every state change.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ConstructorInit extends Component {
  // ❌ ANTI-PATTERN: captures args.score ONCE at construction time
  // If the parent re-renders with a new score value, this won't update
  @tracked localScore;

  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args);
    this.localScore = args.score; // Snapshot, NOT a live binding
  }

  // ✅ CORRECT: getter always reads the current arg value
  get currentScore() {
    return this.args.score;
  }

  <template>
    <p>From constructor (stale after parent re-renders): {{this.localScore}}</p>
    <p>From getter (always fresh): {{this.currentScore}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
The constructor runs exactly once per component instance. Assigning `args.score` to a tracked property in the constructor takes a one-time snapshot. If the parent changes and passes a new `score` arg, `this.localScore` remains at its initial value — it has no live binding to the arg. Instead, use a getter that reads `this.args.score` directly, which re-evaluates on every render and always reflects the current arg value.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class PersistentState extends Component {
  // This @tracked state persists across parent re-renders
  // as long as the component instance is not destroyed and recreated
  @tracked localCount = 0;

  @action
  increment() {
    this.localCount += 1;
  }

  <template>
    <p>@arg from parent: {{@parentData}}</p>
    {{!-- localCount survives parent re-renders --}}
    <p>Local count (persists): {{this.localCount}}</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.increment}}>+1</button>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer maintains component *identity* — if the same component appears at the same position in the template across re-renders, it keeps the same component instance and all its `@tracked` state. State only resets if the component is *destroyed*: removed from the DOM (via `{{#if}}`), or if its `@key` changes in an `{{each}}` loop. Understanding this distinction is key to predicting when local state survives a parent update.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class StaticTrackedBug extends Component {
  // ❌ WRONG: @tracked on static property is not supported
  // static @tracked matchCount = 0;
  // This would throw: @tracked can only be used on instance properties

  // ✅ CORRECT alternative: use a tracked property on a Service for shared state
  // Or use a module-level TrackedObject/TrackedArray

  // Instance @tracked — works correctly
  @tracked instanceScore = 0;

  <template>
    <p>Instance score: {{this.instanceScore}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
`@tracked` is designed to work with JavaScript class *instance* properties — it instruments the getter/setter on the class prototype relative to an instance. Static properties belong to the class constructor object, not to instances. Glimmer's autotracking system builds its dependency graph around component instances, so there is no valid context to track a static property. For shared reactive state across components, the correct pattern is an injected Ember Service with `@tracked` instance properties.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { TrackedArray, TrackedObject, TrackedMap, TrackedSet } from 'tracked-built-ins';

export default class TrackedBuiltinsDemo extends Component {
  // Each of these reacts to native mutation methods
  players = new TrackedArray(['Tamim', 'Liton']);
  stats = new TrackedObject({ runs: 0, wickets: 0 });
  teamIds = new TrackedSet([1, 2, 3]);
  scoreByOver = new TrackedMap([[1, 6], [2, 8]]);

  @action
  update() {
    this.players.push('Shakib');      // reactive ✅
    this.stats.runs += 10;           // reactive ✅
    this.teamIds.add(4);             // reactive ✅
    this.scoreByOver.set(3, 12);     // reactive ✅
  }

  <template>
    <p>Players: {{this.players.length}}</p>
    <p>Runs: {{this.stats.runs}}</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.update}}>Update</button>
  </template>
}
```
`tracked-built-ins` provides reactive drop-in replacements for `Array`, `Object`, `Map`, and `Set`. The core problem they solve: Glimmer's `@tracked` only watches the *reference* of a value, not its internal contents. By overriding native mutation methods (like `push`, `set`, `delete`) to bump internal revision tags, these classes allow natural, idiomatic JavaScript mutation while still triggering Glimmer's reactivity system.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class GranularitySmell extends Component {
  // ❌ SMELL: one giant object — updating ANY field invalidates ALL getters
  @tracked matchState = {
    runs: 0, wickets: 0, overs: 0, balls: 0,
    batsman1: null, batsman2: null, bowler: null,
    powerplay: true, drs: 2, targetRuns: null,
    // ... 15 more fields
  };

  // ✅ BETTER: separate tracked properties for independent state
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;
  @tracked overs = 0;
  // Changing 'runs' only invalidates getters that read 'runs'
  // Changing 'wickets' only invalidates getters that read 'wickets'

  <template>
    <p>{{this.runs}}/{{this.wickets}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
When you store all state in one `@tracked` object, every spread-update replaces the entire object. Any getter that reads `this.matchState` is invalidated on every update — even if it only uses one field. With separate `@tracked` properties, Glimmer can invalidate getters and template expressions with surgical precision: changing `runs` only re-evaluates consumers that read `runs`. The rule of thumb: separate tracked properties for independently changing values, group into an object only when they always change together (like coordinates).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency';

export default class TaskInteraction extends Component {
