  <template>
    <div class="p-4 border rounded">
      <p>Team: {{@teamName}}</p>
      <p>Score: {{this.score}}</p>
      <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+1 Run</button>
    </div>
  </template>
}

{{!-- In parent template: two independent instances --}}
{{!-- <IndependentState @teamName="Bangladesh" /> --}}
{{!-- <IndependentState @teamName="Sri Lanka" /> --}}
```
`@tracked` is an *instance property* decorator. Each time Glimmer creates a component instance (on first render), the JavaScript class constructor runs and creates a new independent `score` value. Incrementing the Bangladesh team's score has absolutely no effect on the Sri Lanka instance. This is the fundamental difference between local component state (`@tracked`) and shared application state (a service's `@tracked` property, which all components share through injection).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class DestroyAndRecreate extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;

  @action
  addRun() { this.score += 1; }

  <template>
    <p>Score: {{this.score}}</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+1 Run</button>
  </template>
}

// PARENT TEMPLATE:
// {{#if this.showScoreboard}}
//   <DestroyAndRecreate /> {{!-- When showScoreboard becomes false, instance is destroyed --}}
// {{/if}}   {{!-- When showScoreboard becomes true again, NEW instance is created --}}
//            {{!-- Score resets to 0 because constructor runs again --}}
```
When a component is removed from the DOM (e.g., by an `{{#if}}` becoming false), Glimmer calls `willDestroy` and tears down the component instance. All `@tracked` properties are part of that instance and are garbage collected. When the component is re-added to the DOM, a brand new instance is constructed with all `@tracked` properties at their initial values. State does NOT persist across destroy/recreate cycles unless you save it externally (to a service or route model) before destruction.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ChildWithOwnState extends Component {
  // This survives parent re-renders as long as the component
  // is not removed from the DOM
  @tracked localScore = 0;

  @action increment() { this.localScore += 1; }

  <template>
    {{!-- @parentProp updates when parent re-renders --}}
    <p>From parent: {{@parentProp}}</p>
    {{!-- localScore is unaffected by parent re-renders --}}
    <p>Local: {{this.localScore}}</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.increment}}>+1</button>
  </template>
}
```
Parent re-renders do NOT reset child `@tracked` state, as long as the child component remains in the DOM at the same template position. Glimmer reconciles the component tree and reuses existing instances where possible. New `@args` values flow down to the child, but the child's instance properties remain untouched. State resets only if the component is destroyed: removed via `{{#if}}` or given a new `@key` in an `{{each}}` loop.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ReactiveGetter extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 50;
  @tracked balls = 30;

  // This getter becomes reactive NOT because of any special decorator
  // but because it READS @tracked properties during evaluation
  get strikeRate() {
    // When this getter runs, Glimmer's tracking frame is active
    // Reading this.runs → registers 'runs' tag as dependency
    // Reading this.balls → registers 'balls' tag as dependency
    return ((this.runs / this.balls) * 100).toFixed(1);
  }

  <template>
    <p>SR: {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer's tracking frame is a global, implicit context that is active during any template rendering or getter memoization evaluation. The `@tracked` decorator instruments property access so that any *read* of a tracked property while the frame is active causes that property's tag to be registered with the frame's consumer. It is the act of *reading* that creates the dependency link — not any explicit subscription call. This is why even plain `get` accessors become reactive as long as they read tracked data.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ConditionalTracking extends Component {
  @tracked showDetails = false;
  @tracked playerName = 'Tamim';
  @tracked runs = 0;

  @action toggle() { this.showDetails = !this.showDetails; }

  <template>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.toggle}}>Toggle</button>
    {{!-- The {{#if}} condition is ALWAYS evaluated — showDetails is always tracked --}}
    {{#if this.showDetails}}
      {{!-- 'playerName' and 'runs' are ONLY tracked when this branch is rendered --}}
      <p>{{this.playerName}}: {{this.runs}} runs</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer only tracks properties that are *actually read* during a render pass. If `showDetails` is `false`, the `{{#if}}` block's content is not rendered, so `playerName` and `runs` are never read and never registered as dependencies for that block. When `showDetails` becomes `true`, the block renders for the first time, reads `playerName` and `runs`, and now tracks them. This is called "branch-aware tracking" — only the active code path creates dependencies.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class IsolatedComponent extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;

  @action
  addRun() {
    this.score += 1;
  }

  // ❌ WRONG pattern (caller perspective — don't do this):
  // const comp = getComponentSomehow();
  // comp.addRun(); // Bypasses data flow, creates tight coupling

  // ✅ CORRECT: parent uses @args to request state change
  // Child calls this.args.onRunAdded?.() and parent updates its own tracked state

  <template>
