```
The spreadsheet model is the most intuitive way to think about `@tracked`: each `@tracked` property is a cell with a value. Each getter is a formula cell that automatically recalculates when its input cells change. The template is the visible output that auto-updates. You never manually trigger updates — you just change the source value (the cell) and everything downstream (formulas, display) refreshes automatically. This push-based reactivity is what "reactive programming" means in practice.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ValidatedInput extends Component {
  @tracked _playerAge = 18;

  // Setter runs inline validation — no @action needed
  set playerAge(value) {
    const parsed = parseInt(value, 10);
    // Validation enforced at the storage layer
    if (!isNaN(parsed) && parsed >= 16 && parsed <= 45) {
      this._playerAge = parsed;
    }
    // Silently ignores invalid values — or you could set an error tracked prop
  }

  get playerAge() {
    return this._playerAge;
  }

  <template>
    <input
      type="number"
      value={{this.playerAge}}
      min="16"
      max="45"
      {{on "input" (fn (mut this.playerAge))}}
      class="border rounded px-2 py-1"
    />
    <p>Age: {{this.playerAge}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
A setter is useful when the validation rule is simple, always applies, and should be invisible to callers. The caller just assigns `this.playerAge = value` and the setter silently enforces constraints. An `@action` method is better when validation needs to show user feedback, set error messages, or perform side effects like API calls. Setters are also useful with the `{{mut}}` helper for two-way binding scenarios.

```gjs
