Components are created and destroyed with the UI — their `@tracked` state is ephemeral and instance-local. Services are singletons that live for the application's lifetime — their `@tracked` state is shared across every component that injects them. Use component state for UI-only concerns (accordion open, loading spinner, local form draft). Use service state for application-wide concerns (current user, live score, auth status, selected match).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class SyncVsAsync extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;

  @action
  addTen() {
    this.runs += 1;  // Sync: tag bumped, consumers marked dirty
    this.runs += 1;  // Sync: tag bumped again
    this.runs += 1;  // Sync: tag bumped again
    // At this point: this.runs === 3 in memory
    // But the DOM still shows 0 — re-render hasn't fired yet

    console.log('Before yield:', this.runs); // 3
    // ... after microtask ...
    // DOM updates to 3 in ONE render pass
    this.runs += 7;  // More sync bumps
    // Final re-render: DOM shows 10 in one pass
    console.log('After actions: runs =', this.runs); // 10
  }

  <template><p>{{this.runs}}</p><button type="button" {{on "click" this.addTen}}>+10</button></template>
}
```
Tag invalidation is *synchronous*: the moment you assign to a tracked property, its revision tag increments and all consumers are immediately marked as dirty in memory. However, Glimmer queues the actual DOM re-render as a microtask (scheduled via `Promise.resolve()`). This deferred rendering is what enables batching — all synchronous assignments in one event handler complete before the single re-render pass runs. The separation of "invalidate" (sync) from "render" (async) is what guarantees UI consistency.

