Glimmer's tracking is at the reference level. `this.team` is tracked — but `this.team.score` and `this.team.score.runs` are plain JavaScript properties with no revision tags. Any mutation below the tracked level is invisible to Glimmer. You must replace every object in the path from the tracked property down to the changed value. For frequently mutated deep structures, `TrackedObject` or a flatter state design is a better architectural choice.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class NoStaleClosure extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;

  @action
  scheduleDelayedAddRun() {
    setTimeout(() => {
      // In Glimmer: this.score reads the CURRENT value at call time
      // NOT a captured snapshot from when setTimeout was scheduled
      this.score += 1;
      // This always adds 1 to the current score,
      // regardless of how many times score changed during the delay
      console.log('Updated score:', this.score);
    }, 1000);
  }

  // In React useEffect/useState, reading 'score' inside setTimeout
  // would capture a stale value from the closure's creation time.
  // You'd need useRef or functional state updates to work around this.

  <template>
    <p>{{this.score}}</p>
    <button type="button" {{on "click" this.scheduleDelayedAddRun}}>+1 after 1s</button>
  </template>
}
```
In React, `useState` values inside closures are snapshots — they capture the value at the time the closure was created. If state changes before the callback fires, the callback sees the old value. Glimmer's `@tracked` properties are accessed via `this`, and `this` always points to the live component instance. Reading `this.score` inside a `setTimeout` callback always returns the *current* value at call time, not a stale snapshot.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class DeriveVsStore extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 45;
  @tracked balls = 30;
  @tracked wickets = 2;

