  @action
  addRun() {
    this.runs += 1;
  }

  // ❌ Avoid — plain method loses `this` when passed as callback
  // addRunPlain() { this.runs += 1; }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}}>Add Run</button>
    <p>Runs: {{this.runs}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
In Glimmer, when you pass a method as an event listener via `{{on}}`, JavaScript extracts it from the object, losing its `this` context. `@action` wraps the method with `Function.prototype.bind(this)` at decoration time, so `this` always refers to the component instance. Without `@action`, `this.runs` inside the handler would be `undefined` and assignment would silently fail or throw. Using `@action` also signals intent to other developers that this method is a user-facing event handler.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class BowlingStatsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked wickets = 3;
  @tracked overs = 10;

  // Glimmer records that this getter reads `wickets` and `overs`
  get strikeRate() {
    return this.overs > 0 ? (this.overs * 6) / this.wickets : 0;
  }

  <template>
    <p>Strike Rate: {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer's autotracking system maintains a dependency graph. The first time `strikeRate` is called, the runtime wraps the execution in a tracking frame. Every `@tracked` property read inside that frame — `wickets` and `overs` — is registered as a dependency. The getter's result is memoized. When `wickets` or `overs` changes, the runtime marks those tags as dirty, invalidating any memoized getter that consumed them. The next template render re-invokes the getter, which rebuilds its dependency list fresh. No subscription setup is needed; it is entirely automatic.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class InningsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;
  @tracked balls = 0;

  @action
  recordBoundary() {
    // All three assignments happen synchronously
    this.runs += 4;
    this.wickets += 0;
    this.balls += 1;
    // Only ONE re-render is scheduled after this action completes
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.recordBoundary}}>Four</button>
    <p>{{this.runs}}/{{this.wickets}} ({{this.balls}} balls)</p>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer batches all tag invalidations that occur within a single synchronous execution context. When `recordBoundary` runs, all three `@tracked` assignments mark their tags as dirty, but Glimmer defers the re-render until the current call stack completes. After the `@action` returns, one consolidated re-render pass processes all dirty tags together. This prevents intermediate renders where, for example, `runs` is updated but `balls` is not yet, which would show a temporarily inconsistent UI.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class PlayerCardComponent extends Component {
  // @args.player comes from parent — can change any time
  // @tracked local state is independent
  @tracked isExpanded = false;

  @action
  toggleExpand() {
    this.isExpanded = !this.isExpanded;
  }

  <template>
    <h2>{{@player.name}}</h2>
    {{#if this.isExpanded}}
      <p>Avg: {{@player.battingAvg}}</p>
    {{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" this.toggleExpand}}>Details</button>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer components keep their identity (and therefore their `@tracked` state) as long as they remain in the DOM at the same position. When a parent re-renders and passes updated `@args`, Glimmer updates the args object on the existing component instance — it does not destroy and recreate the component. So `isExpanded` retains its value across parent updates. Only if the component is removed from the DOM and re-inserted (or if `{{#if}}` toggles it out and back) is the instance recreated and local state reset.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class MatchDisplayComponent extends Component {
  // ❌ Bug — captured once at construction, never updates
  // @tracked matchName = this.args.match.name;

  // ✅ Correct — getter always reads current args value
  get matchName() {
    return this.args.match?.name ?? 'Unknown Match';
  }

  <template>
    <h1>{{this.matchName}}</h1>
  </template>
}
```
The constructor runs exactly once when the component is instantiated. If you assign `this.trackedProp = this.args.something` there, the value is copied at that moment. Later, when the parent passes a different `@args.something`, your `@tracked` property still holds the old value — the component instance is not recreated, so the constructor never runs again. The correct pattern is to use a getter that reads `this.args` directly, which participates in autotracking and always returns the current argument value on every render.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class LiveScoreComponent extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;
  #intervalId = null; // plain property, not tracked

  @action
  startPolling() {
    this.#intervalId = setInterval(() => {
      this.score += 1; // updates @tracked — fine while alive
    }, 1000);
  }

  willDestroy() {
    super.willDestroy();
    clearInterval(this.#intervalId); // stop mutating @tracked after destroy
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.startPolling}}>Start</button>
    <p>Score: {{this.score}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
`willDestroy` is the right place to cancel timers, abort fetch requests, or remove event listeners that were set up during the component's life. The critical reason is that updating a `@tracked` property on a destroyed component throws an assertion error in development. Storing the interval ID in a plain (non-tracked) property keeps it out of Glimmer's dependency graph — only values that affect the template need `@tracked`. `willDestroy` must call `super.willDestroy()` first to let Glimmer complete its own teardown.

```gjs
// match-session.js — Ember service
import Service from '@ember/service';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class MatchSessionService extends Service {
  @tracked currentMatchId = null;
  @tracked isLive = false;

  setMatch(id) {
    this.currentMatchId = id;
    this.isLive = true;
  }
}

// ScoreboardComponent.gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { service } from '@ember/service';

export default class ScoreboardComponent extends Component {
  @service matchSession;

  <template>
    {{#if this.matchSession.isLive}}
      <p>Live: Match {{this.matchSession.currentMatchId}}</p>
    {{/if}}
