```
`@tracked` is a general-purpose decorator from `@glimmer/tracking` — it is not tied to the `Component` base class. Any JavaScript class can use it. When a component template reads a `@tracked` property from an injected service, the autotracking system registers that service tag as a dependency of the template. When the service property changes, all components that read it are automatically re-rendered. This is how Glimmer enables shared reactive state across multiple components without a separate state management library.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

class BasePlayerComponent extends Component {
  @tracked playerName = '';
  @tracked isSelected = false;

  @action
  select() {
    this.isSelected = true;
  }
}

export default class BatsmanCardComponent extends BasePlayerComponent {
  @tracked battingAvg = 0; // child adds its own tracked property

  get displayName() {
    // reads inherited @tracked playerName — fully reactive
    return `${this.playerName} (Avg: ${this.battingAvg})`;
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.displayName}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.select}}>Select</button>
  </template>
}
```
`@tracked` decorators on a parent class are fully inherited by child classes. The autotracking tags are stored on the prototype chain, so reading `this.playerName` in a child getter correctly registers the parent's tracked tag as a dependency. Child classes can add their own `@tracked` properties without affecting the parent's reactivity. Overriding a `@tracked` property in a child class replaces the parent's tag with a new one, so both parent and child instances remain independent.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class TeamListComponent extends Component {
  @tracked selectedTeam = null;

  @action
  selectTeam(team) {
    this.selectedTeam = team;
  }

  <template>
    {{#each @teams as |team|}}
      {{! ✅ fn creates a new function with `team` pre-applied }}
      <button {{on "click" (fn this.selectTeam team)}}>
        {{team.name}}
      </button>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
DOM event handlers receive a single argument: the native `Event` object. If you write `{{on "click" this.selectTeam}}`, the `@action` receives the click event, not the `team` value you want. The `{{fn}}` helper is Glimmer's equivalent of `Function.prototype.bind` for templates — it returns a new function with the specified arguments pre-applied. When the button is clicked, the browser calls the bound function, which in turn calls `selectTeam(team, event)`. This pattern avoids creating arrow functions inside templates, which would generate new function references on every render.

```gjs
// match-score-test.js
import { module, test } from 'qunit';
import { setupRenderingTest } from 'ember-qunit';
import { render, click, settled } from '@ember/test-helpers';
import ScoreComponent from './score-component';

module('ScoreComponent', function (hooks) {
  setupRenderingTest(hooks);

  test('adds run on click', async function (assert) {
    await render(<template><ScoreComponent /></template>);
    await click('[data-test-add-run]');
    // `click` internally calls `settled()` — DOM is already updated
    assert.dom('[data-test-runs]').hasText('1');
  });

  test('manual @tracked update needs settled', async function (assert) {
    const component = ...; // get instance
    component.runs = 5;
    await settled(); // wait for Glimmer to flush the re-render
    assert.dom('[data-test-runs]').hasText('5');
  });
});
```
Glimmer's re-renders are asynchronous — tag invalidation is synchronous, but the actual DOM update is scheduled as a microtask. In tests, after you directly set a `@tracked` property, the DOM has not yet updated. `settled()` returns a Promise that resolves after all pending renders, timers, and async tasks have completed. Test helpers like `click()` and `fillIn()` call `settled()` internally, so you only need to call it explicitly when you mutate state outside of a test helper action.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class InningsTrackerComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked balls = 0;

  get strikeRate() {
    // Always computed fresh from current @tracked values
    return this.balls > 0 ? ((this.runs / this.balls) * 100).toFixed(2) : '0.00';
  }

  @action
  recordDot() {
    this.balls += 1;
    // strikeRate getter will reflect this immediately on next read
  }

  <template>
    <p>SR: {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.recordDot}}>Dot</button>
  </template>
}
```
Autotracking uses a tag-based invalidation system. When `balls` changes, its tag revision number increments. The memoized result of `strikeRate` is stored alongside the tag revision it was computed with. Before returning the cached value, Glimmer checks if any consumed tag's current revision is higher than what was recorded — if so, the cache is stale and the getter re-runs. This check is O(1) per tag, making it extremely fast. There is no window of time where a getter can return a value computed from outdated `@tracked` state.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class LiveScoreComponent extends Component {
  @tracked score = 145;

  // ✅ Push-based: re-render only happens when score actually changes
  @action
  updateScore(newScore) {
    this.score = newScore;
  }

  // ❌ Polling (never do this): check state every N ms regardless of change
  // constructor() { super(...arguments); setInterval(() => this.checkScore(), 100); }

  <template>
    <p>Score: {{this.score}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Polling re-evaluates state on a timer regardless of whether anything changed, wasting CPU cycles and causing unnecessary renders. `@tracked` is push-based: nothing happens until a `@tracked` property is assigned a new value. At that moment, the tag is marked dirty and a re-render is scheduled. If the value assigned is identical to the current value, Glimmer still invalidates (it does not deep-compare), but the render cycle is still far cheaper than continuous polling. This model scales efficiently — hundreds of `@tracked` properties across dozens of components have zero overhead between updates.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class MatchSummaryComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;
  @tracked extras = 0;
  @tracked overs = 0;

  @action
  recordOver(overData) {
    this.runs += overData.runs;      // tag dirty
    this.wickets += overData.wickets; // tag dirty
    this.extras += overData.extras;   // tag dirty
    this.overs += 1;                  // tag dirty
    // ONE re-render scheduled after this function returns
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.runs}}/{{this.wickets}} in {{this.overs}} overs</p>
  </template>
}
```
Glimmer does not re-render synchronously on each assignment. Each `@tracked` write marks that property's tag as dirty but does not immediately trigger DOM updates. Re-renders are scheduled asynchronously (typically as a microtask or via `requestAnimationFrame`). All four dirty tags accumulate before the render pass runs. The renderer then processes all stale getters and template bindings in one sweep. This batching is automatic and requires no explicit transaction API — it is simply a consequence of the asynchronous render scheduling model.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { task } from 'ember-concurrency';

export default class MatchLoaderComponent extends Component {
  fetchMatch = task(this, { drop: true }, async (matchId) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`);
    return response.json();
  });

  <template>
    {{#if this.fetchMatch.isRunning}}
      <p>Loading match data...</p>
    {{else}}
      <button {{on "click" (fn this.fetchMatch.perform @matchId)}}>
        Load Match
      </button>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if this.fetchMatch.last.value}}
      <p>{{this.fetchMatch.last.value.name}}</p>
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
ember-concurrency decorates task state properties — `isRunning`, `isIdle`, `last`, `error` — with `@tracked` internally. This means the template reading `this.fetchMatch.isRunning` registers that tag as a dependency. When the task starts or completes, ember-concurrency sets `isRunning` which invalidates the tag and schedules a re-render automatically. You do not need to manually manage loading booleans alongside task invocations — the task object itself is a reactive state machine that Glimmer's autotracking understands natively.

```gjs
// ✅ Good use — local UI state owned by one component
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ScoreCardComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isExpanded = false; // UI-only, nobody else needs this
}

// For cross-component shared state — use a Service, not @tracked in a component
// match-store.js
import Service from '@ember/service';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class MatchStoreService extends Service {
  @tracked liveMatches = [];
  @tracked selectedMatchId = null;
}
```
`@tracked` in a component is scoped to that component instance — it disappears when the component is destroyed and is invisible to other components unless explicitly passed via `@args`. For state that must persist across navigation, be shared between unrelated components, or survive component lifecycle, use an Ember Service with `@tracked` properties. Services are singletons in Ember's container and are injected wherever needed. The combination of `@tracked` on a Service with Glimmer's autotracking gives you reactive global state without a third-party library.

```gjs
// Ember @tracked — class property decorator
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
class ScoreComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0; // reads/writes look like plain JS
  get total() { return this.runs + this.extras; } // getter = derived signal
}

// SolidJS equivalent (for reference only — not Ember code)
// const [runs, setRuns] = createSignal(0);
// const total = createMemo(() => runs() + extras());

// Angular equivalent (for reference only)
// runs = signal(0);
// total = computed(() => this.runs() + this.extras());
```
All three systems implement fine-grained reactivity with a dependency-tracking graph. The key difference is ergonomics: Ember `@tracked` uses native property access (`this.runs`) for both reads and writes, making it feel like plain JavaScript. SolidJS signals require calling a getter function (`runs()`) and a separate setter (`setRuns(n)`). Angular signals also use function-call syntax for reads. Glimmer's approach (pioneered before signals became a universal term) is the most transparent — no special syntax at the call site. The underlying mechanism — tracking reads, invalidating dependents on write — is conceptually identical across all three.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class DebugComponent extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;

  get formattedScore() {
    // This log fires every time the getter cache is invalidated
    console.log('formattedScore computed', this.score);
    return `Score: ${this.score}`;
  }

  // ✅ Better debugging: use browser DevTools reactive breakpoints
  // or log only inside @action where you control when it runs

  <template>
    <p>{{this.formattedScore}}</p>
  </template>
}
```
Getters in Glimmer are memoized but re-run every time a consumed `@tracked` tag is invalidated. During development, Glimmer may invoke getters more times than you expect — during initial render, during testing, and sometimes for internal consistency checks. A `console.log` inside a getter logs each invocation, which can appear to be "too many" re-runs. This is not a bug; it is correct behavior. For actual debugging, prefer logging inside `@action` methods (which run only in response to explicit user actions) or use Ember Inspector to observe component state.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { TrackedObject } from 'tracked-built-ins';

export default class PlayerStatsComponent extends Component {
  // TrackedObject wraps each property with @tracked internally
  stats = new TrackedObject({
    runs: 0,
    wickets: 0,
    catches: 0,
  });

  @action
  addRun() {
    this.stats.runs += 1; // ✅ Mutation triggers re-render
  }

  get totalContributions() {
    return this.stats.runs + this.stats.wickets + this.stats.catches;
  }

  <template>
    <p>Runs: {{this.stats.runs}}</p>
    <p>Total: {{this.totalContributions}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+Run</button>
  </template>
}
```
`TrackedObject` from `tracked-built-ins` is a Proxy-based wrapper that intercepts property reads and writes. Each property access registers a tracked tag, and each property assignment invalidates that tag. This allows you to mutate object properties directly (`this.stats.runs += 1`) while still triggering re-renders — unlike a plain `@tracked` object where you must replace the entire reference. Use `TrackedObject` when your data model has many properties and replacing the whole object on each change would be cumbersome or expensive.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class MatchTimerComponent extends Component {
  @tracked elapsed = 0;
  #timerId = null;

  // ✅ No @action needed — constructor is called by the framework with correct `this`
  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args);
    this.#timerId = setInterval(() => {
      this.elapsed += 1;
    }, 1000);
  }

  // ✅ No @action needed — Glimmer calls willDestroy directly on the instance
  willDestroy() {
    super.willDestroy();
    clearInterval(this.#timerId);
