```
A plain `@tracked` property tracks the reference stored in it, not the contents of that reference. When you mutate a property of the stored object (`this.match.venue = venue`), the reference in `this.match` does not change — Glimmer sees the same object and the tag is not invalidated, so no re-render occurs. Assigning a new object (`this.match = { ...this.match, venue }`) replaces the reference, which increments the tag revision and triggers re-render. This is why spread-update or full replacement is the correct pattern for `@tracked` objects.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ScoreboardComponent extends Component {
