}
```
With a single `@tracked` object, every property mutation requires replacing the entire object reference. Any getter reading that object is invalidated even if it only cares about one field. Granular `@tracked` properties give Glimmer's autotracking system precise information: `runRate` tags `runs` and `overs` but not `isExpanded`, so toggling expansion never triggers `runRate` to recompute. This results in fewer unnecessary getter evaluations and more efficient renders, especially in components with many derived values.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ProxyDemoComponent extends Component {
  // @tracked stores the Proxy reference, not the underlying object
  @tracked playerProxy = new Proxy(
    { name: 'Kohli', runs: 0 },
    {
      set(target, key, value) {
        target[key] = value;
        return true;
      }
    }
  );

  @action
  updateRuns() {
    // ❌ Proxy mutation does NOT invalidate @tracked tag — only reference change does
    // this.playerProxy.runs += 1;

    // ✅ Replace the Proxy reference — tag invalidated
    const target = { ...this.playerProxy };
    target.runs += 1;
    this.playerProxy = new Proxy(target, { set(t, k, v) { t[k] = v; return true; } });
  }
}
```
A plain `@tracked` property only tracks its own reference. Intercepting mutations via a Proxy does not notify Glimmer's autotracking system unless you explicitly consume and invalidate `@tracked` tags inside the Proxy trap. `TrackedObject` from `tracked-built-ins` is the correct solution — it uses a Proxy with Glimmer tracking built into its getter and setter traps. Rolling your own reactive Proxy is complex and error-prone; prefer `TrackedObject` for deep reactivity needs.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';

export default class MatchBadgeComponent extends Component {
  // No @tracked — getter only reads @args
  get matchLabel() {
    const { format, venue } = this.args;
    return `${format} at ${venue}`;
  }

  <template>
    <span>{{this.matchLabel}}</span>
  </template>
}
```
`this.args` in a Glimmer component is itself a tracked object — each argument property has an internal `@tracked`-like tag managed by the framework. When the parent re-renders and passes different values for `format` or `venue`, those argument tags are invalidated. Any getter (or template expression) that consumed those tags is marked as stale and re-runs on the next render. You do not need local `@tracked` properties for values derived purely from `@args` — getters reading args are already fully reactive without any additional decorator.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { cached } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class TournamentStandingsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked matches = [];

  // Plain getter: recomputes every time the template renders (even if matches unchanged)
  // get standings() { return this.#computeHeavy(); }

  // @cached getter: recomputes ONLY when `matches` tag is invalidated
  @cached
  get standings() {
    // Expensive: sorts and groups hundreds of match records
    return [...this.matches]
      .sort((a, b) => b.points - a.points)
      .map((m, i) => ({ ...m, rank: i + 1 }));
  }

  <template>
    {{#each this.standings as |team|}}
      <p>{{team.rank}}. {{team.name}}</p>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
Without `@cached`, a getter re-runs every time the render pass evaluates the template, even if none of its tracked dependencies changed. For lightweight getters, this is fine. For expensive computations — large array sorts, complex string formatting, or heavy calculations — `@cached` memoizes the result and only recomputes when a consumed `@tracked` tag is actually invalidated. The `@cached` decorator adds a small memory overhead (storing the cached value), so only apply it to genuinely expensive getters, not every getter in your component.

```gjs
// ParentComponent.gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import ScoreEditorComponent from './score-editor';

export default class ParentComponent extends Component {
  @tracked showEditor = true;

  @action toggle() { this.showEditor = !this.showEditor; }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.toggle}}>Toggle Editor</button>
    {{#if this.showEditor}}
      <ScoreEditorComponent /> {{! New instance each time — @tracked resets }}
    {{/if}}
  </template>
}

// If you need persistent state, lift it to parent @args or a service:
// <ScoreEditorComponent @score={{this.persistedScore}} @onUpdate={{this.saveScore}} />
```
Glimmer destroys a component instance when it leaves the DOM (e.g., when `{{#if}}` evaluates to false). All `@tracked` properties on that instance are garbage collected along with it. When `{{#if}}` becomes true again, a brand new instance is created with fresh initial values. This is the correct behavior — Glimmer does not cache destroyed component instances. To persist state across toggle cycles, lift the state out of the component: store it in the parent as `@tracked` and pass it down as `@args`, or use an Ember Service.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreConsistencyComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 100;
  @tracked wickets = 3;

  get summary() {
    // Always reads both values from the same render pass — always consistent
    return `${this.runs}/${this.wickets}`;
  }

  @action
  recordDismissal(runsAdded) {
    this.runs += runsAdded;
    this.wickets += 1;
    // DOM still shows old values here — re-render is pending
  }

  <template><p>{{this.summary}}</p></template>
}
```
Glimmer's render cycle is synchronous and non-interruptible once it begins. All `@tracked` mutations within an `@action` accumulate dirty tags but do not trigger partial renders. Only after the action's call stack completes does Glimmer schedule a render. That render reads all tracked values in a single pass — `runs` and `wickets` are always read together within one consistent snapshot. There is no time between renders where `runs` has been updated but `wickets` has not, which would display `104/3` when the correct state is `104/4`. This atomic rendering guarantee eliminates an entire class of UI consistency bugs.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

// Option A — boolean flag
export default class OptionAComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isLoading = false;
  // ❌ Cannot distinguish idle vs error vs success without extra flags
}

// Option B — status string enum (✅ Recommended for async operations)
export default class MatchLoaderComponent extends Component {
  @tracked status = 'idle'; // 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error'
  @tracked errorMessage = '';

  get isLoading() { return this.status === 'loading'; }
  get isError()   { return this.status === 'error'; }
  get isSuccess() { return this.status === 'success'; }

  @action
  async fetchMatch(id) {
    this.status = 'loading';
    try {
      const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}`);
      await res.json();
      this.status = 'success';
    } catch (err) {
      this.errorMessage = err.message;
      this.status = 'error';
    }
  }

  <template>
    {{#if this.isLoading}}<p>Loading...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.isError}}<p class="text-red-600">{{this.errorMessage}}</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.isSuccess}}<p>Match loaded!</p>{{/if}}
  </template>
}
```
Use a boolean `isLoading` only for the simplest cases where there are exactly two states. The moment you need to handle errors or distinguish idle from loaded, a single boolean forces you to add more flags (`isError`, `isSuccess`) which can conflict (e.g., both true). A status string enum is a finite state machine — only one state can be active at a time, eliminating impossible states. Boolean getters derived from the status string keep template expressions clean while the single `@tracked status` property remains the source of truth.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { TrackedArray } from 'tracked-built-ins';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

// Option A — plain @tracked array (replace reference on each mutation)
class OptionAComponent extends Component {
  @tracked players = [];

  @action addPlayer(p) {
    this.players = [...this.players, p]; // must spread — mutation won't react
  }
}

// Option B — TrackedArray (mutate directly) ✅ Recommended when list changes frequently
export default class BattingLineupComponent extends Component {
  players = new TrackedArray([]);

  @action addPlayer(player) {
    this.players.push(player); // ✅ push/pop/splice all trigger re-render
  }

  @action removePlayer(index) {
    this.players.splice(index, 1);
  }

  <template>
    {{#each this.players as |player|}}
      <p>{{player.name}}</p>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
Use a plain `@tracked` array when mutations are infrequent and you prefer the immutable update pattern (spread, filter, map). This works well for small lists and keeps code predictable. Use `TrackedArray` when you need frequent mutations like `push`, `splice`, or `sort` and don't want to spread large arrays on each change. `TrackedArray` also provides item-level granularity — only the parts of the template reading a changed index re-render, not the entire list. Avoid `TrackedArray` if you frequently replace the entire list; a plain `@tracked` array is simpler there.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { TrackedObject } from 'tracked-built-ins';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

// Option A — plain @tracked object
class OptionAComponent extends Component {
  @tracked match = { venue: 'MCG', format: 'Test', runs: 0 };

  @action updateRuns(r) {
    this.match = { ...this.match, runs: r }; // whole object replaced
  }
}

// Option B — TrackedObject ✅ Recommended for objects with frequent field mutations
export default class MatchStatsComponent extends Component {
  stats = new TrackedObject({ venue: 'MCG', format: 'Test', runs: 0 });

  @action updateRuns(r) {
    this.stats.runs = r; // ✅ direct mutation — only `runs` tag invalidated
  }

  get summary() {
    return `${this.stats.runs} runs at ${this.stats.venue}`;
  }

  <template><p>{{this.summary}}</p></template>
}
```
Use a plain `@tracked` object when the object is replaced wholesale (e.g., fetched from an API) or when it has only a few properties that change together. Use `TrackedObject` when individual fields are updated independently and frequently — it provides per-property reactivity, so updating `runs` only invalidates getters that read `runs`, not those reading `venue`. The tradeoff is that `TrackedObject` adds a Proxy wrapper overhead and is slightly harder to reason about for developers unfamiliar with `tracked-built-ins`.

```gjs
// Option A — component local @tracked (✅ for UI-only, ephemeral state)
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class ScoreCardComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isExpanded = false; // only this card cares
}

// Option B — Ember service @tracked (✅ for shared, persistent state)
// live-match-service.js
import Service from '@ember/service';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class LiveMatchService extends Service {
  @tracked currentMatch = null; // multiple components need this
  @tracked liveScore = { runs: 0, wickets: 0 };
}

// AnyComponent.gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { service } from '@ember/service';

export default class HeaderScoreComponent extends Component {
  @service liveMatch;
  <template>
    <span>{{this.liveMatch.liveScore.runs}}/{{this.liveMatch.liveScore.wickets}}</span>
  </template>
}
```
Put state in the component when it is UI-only (expand/collapse, hover, modal open), owned by exactly one component, and can be discarded when the component unmounts. Put state in a service when multiple unrelated components need to read or write it, when it must survive navigation between routes, or when it represents domain/business state (current user, live match data, auth tokens). A common mistake is promoting state to a service prematurely — start local and extract to a service only when you hit a sharing or persistence need.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class BattingStatsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked balls = 0;

  // ❌ Avoid — storing derived value in @tracked forces manual sync
  // @tracked strikeRate = 0;
  // @action addRun() { this.runs++; this.strikeRate = (this.runs/this.balls)*100; }

  // ✅ Correct — getter always derives from source of truth
  get strikeRate() {
    return this.balls > 0 ? ((this.runs / this.balls) * 100).toFixed(2) : '0.00';
  }

  @action addRun() { this.runs += 1; this.balls += 1; }

  <template>
    <p>SR: {{this.strikeRate}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}}>Run</button>
  </template>
}
```
Always prefer a getter for values that can be computed from other `@tracked` properties or `@args`. Storing derived values in `@tracked` creates two problems: you must remember to update the derived property every time a source changes, and if you forget, the UI shows stale data. A getter is always consistent by definition — it computes from the current state at read time. Only store a value in `@tracked` if it is genuinely independent state that cannot be derived from other values (e.g., a user's typed input, a fetched API response).

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class MatchControlComponent extends Component {
  @tracked score = 0;

  // ❌ Plain method — `this` is undefined when passed to {{on}}
  // incrementScore() { this.score += 1; }

  // ✅ @action — `this` is bound at decoration time
  @action
  incrementScore() { this.score += 1; }

  // ✅ Arrow field — `this` captured lexically, no @action needed
  decrementScore = () => { this.score -= 1; };

  // Plain method called internally — no binding issue, @action not needed
  #validateScore() { return this.score >= 0; }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.incrementScore}}>+</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.decrementScore}}>-</button>
  </template>
}
```
`@action` matters specifically when a method is passed as a value (callback or event handler) rather than called directly. When you write `{{on "click" this.incrementScore}}`, the method reference is detached from `this`. `@action` binds `this` at class decoration time, preventing the loss of context. If you call the method directly in another method (`this.incrementScore()`), `this` is preserved by the call syntax and `@action` adds no value. Arrow function class fields (`decrementScore = () => {}`) capture `this` lexically and are a valid alternative to `@action` for event handlers.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreInputComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;

  // Option A — @action decorator (✅ Recommended — idiomatic Ember/Glimmer)
  @action
  addRun() {
    this.runs += 1;
  }

  // Option B — arrow class field (works, but has tradeoffs)
  subtractRun = () => {
    this.runs -= 1;
  };

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+Run</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.subtractRun}}>-Run</button>
  </template>
}
```
Prefer `@action` for event handlers in Glimmer components. It is the idiomatic Ember convention, making code immediately recognizable as a user-facing handler. It also keeps methods on the prototype (memory-efficient for many instances) rather than creating a new function per instance as arrow class fields do. Arrow class fields have a subtle problem: they cannot be overridden by subclasses because they are own properties, not prototype methods. Use arrow class fields sparingly — they are better suited for standalone callbacks passed to non-Glimmer APIs where `this` binding is unpredictable.

```gjs
// ❌ Option A — @tracked in parent, passed via @args (prop drilling)
// Requires parent to own state and thread it through every intermediate component

// ✅ Option B — @tracked in a shared service
// score-service.js
import Service from '@ember/service';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
export default class ScoreService extends Service {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;
}

// ScoreboardComponent.gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { service } from '@ember/service';
export default class ScoreboardComponent extends Component {
  @service score;
  <template><p>{{this.score.runs}}/{{this.score.wickets}}</p></template>
}

// RunRateComponent.gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { service } from '@ember/service';
export default class RunRateComponent extends Component {
  @service score;
  get runRate() { return (this.score.runs / 20).toFixed(2); }
  <template><p>RR: {{this.runRate}}</p></template>
}
```
When multiple components need the same reactive state, a service is the right home. Both `ScoreboardComponent` and `RunRateComponent` inject the same `ScoreService` singleton — when `score.runs` changes, both components re-render automatically. Passing state via `@args` through a common ancestor forces the parent to own unrelated state and creates prop drilling. The service approach scales naturally: a third component can inject `ScoreService` without touching any parent component.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

// Option A — single @tracked object
class OptionAComponent extends Component {
  @tracked formData = { playerName: '', runs: 0, wickets: 0 };
  @action update(field, value) {
    this.formData = { ...this.formData, [field]: value }; // replaces all
  }
}

// Option B — individual @tracked properties (✅ Recommended for most cases)
export default class PlayerFormComponent extends Component {
  @tracked playerName = '';
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;

  get isValid() { return this.playerName.trim().length > 0 && this.runs >= 0; }

  @action setPlayerName(e) { this.playerName = e.target.value; }
  @action setRuns(e)       { this.runs = Number(e.target.value); }

  <template>
    <input value={{this.playerName}} {{on "input" this.setPlayerName}} />
    <input type="number" value={{this.runs}} {{on "input" this.setRuns}} />
  </template>
}
```
Individual `@tracked` properties give Glimmer's autotracking fine-grained dependency information — a getter reading only `runs` is not invalidated when `playerName` changes. This results in fewer unnecessary getter recomputations. A single `@tracked` object is acceptable when the fields always change together (e.g., an API response replaces the whole object) or when there are more than ~10 fields and individual declarations become verbose. For forms with fewer than 8 fields, individual properties are cleaner and more performant.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked, cached } from '@glimmer/tracking';

export default class TournamentStatsComponent extends Component {
  @tracked matches = [];

  // ✅ Plain getter — fast, no need for @cached
  get matchCount() {
    return this.matches.length; // O(1), trivial
  }

  // ✅ @cached — expensive sort + grouping, only recompute when matches changes
  @cached
  get leaderboard() {
    return [...this.matches]
      .sort((a, b) => b.points - a.points)
      .reduce((acc, m) => {
        const group = acc.find(g => g.format === m.format);
        if (group) group.teams.push(m); else acc.push({ format: m.format, teams: [m] });
        return acc;
      }, []);
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.matchCount}} matches</p>
    {{#each this.leaderboard as |group|}}
      <h3>{{group.format}}</h3>
    {{/each}}
  </template>
}
```
Add `@cached` only when the getter performs expensive work: sorting/filtering large arrays (100+ items), heavy string formatting, complex mathematical aggregations, or recursive tree traversal. Plain getters are already memoized in the sense that they re-run only when their tracked dependencies change — but they do re-run on each render pass even if nothing changed. `@cached` adds true memoization with a memory cost (storing the cached value and tracking metadata). For simple property access or arithmetic, `@cached` is premature optimization and adds unnecessary overhead.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class SearchInputComponent extends Component {
  @tracked _query = '';

  // Option A — setter (✅ Good for simple value sync with optional validation)
  get query() { return this._query; }
  set query(value) {
    this._query = value.trimStart(); // normalize on set
  }

  // Option B — @action (✅ Better when you need event object or side effects)
  @action
  updateQuery(event) {
    this._query = event.target.value.trimStart();
    this.args.onSearch?.(this._query); // side effect: notify parent
  }

  <template>
    {{! Setter style — clean, no event object needed }}
    {{! <Input @value={{this.query}} @onChange={{set this "query"}} /> }}

    {{! @action style — full control }}
    <input value={{this._query}} {{on "input" this.updateQuery}} />
  </template>
}
```
Use a setter when you only need to normalize or validate the value on assignment, with no side effects beyond storing it. Setters integrate cleanly with Ember's `<Input>` component and `{{set}}` helper. Use `@action` when you need access to the event object (`event.target.value`, `event.preventDefault()`), need to trigger side effects (calling a parent callback, debouncing a fetch), or need to update multiple `@tracked` properties in response to one input change. For simple text inputs with no side effects, the setter pattern is more concise.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';
import { task, timeout } from 'ember-concurrency';

// Option A — manual @tracked (more boilerplate, error-prone)
class OptionAComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isLoading = false;
  @tracked matchData = null;
  @tracked error = null;

  @action async loadMatch(id) {
    this.isLoading = true;
    this.error = null;
    try {
      this.matchData = await fetch(`/api/matches/${id}`).then(r => r.json());
    } catch(e) { this.error = e.message; }
    finally { this.isLoading = false; }
  }
}

// Option B — ember-concurrency task (✅ Recommended)
export default class MatchViewerComponent extends Component {
  loadMatch = task(this, { drop: true }, async (matchId) => {
    const res = await fetch(`/api/matches/${matchId}`);
    return res.json(); // stored in this.loadMatch.last.value
  });

  <template>
    {{#if this.loadMatch.isRunning}}<p>Loading...</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.loadMatch.last.isError}}<p>Error: {{this.loadMatch.last.error.message}}</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if this.loadMatch.last.value}}<p>{{this.loadMatch.last.value.name}}</p>{{/if}}
    <button {{on "click" (fn this.loadMatch.perform @matchId)}}>Load</button>
  </template>
}
```
Prefer ember-concurrency tasks for async operations. Tasks provide `isRunning`, `last.value`, `last.isError` as reactive tracked state out of the box, eliminating the manual `isLoading`/`error`/`data` trio. Task modifiers like `drop` and `restartable` prevent race conditions without extra code. Use manual `@tracked` only for trivial synchronous state or when you cannot add the ember-concurrency dependency.

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

// Option A — @tracked isDirty flag
class OptionAComponent extends Component {
  @tracked isDirty = false;
  @tracked playerName = '';
  @action update(e) { this.playerName = e.target.value; this.isDirty = true; }
  // ❌ isDirty never goes false if user restores original value
}

// Option B — snapshot comparison (✅ Recommended for accuracy)
export default class PlayerEditorComponent extends Component {
  #savedName = this.args.player.name;
  @tracked playerName = this.args.player.name;

  get isDirty() {
    return this.playerName !== this.#savedName;
  }

  @action update(e) { this.playerName = e.target.value; }

  @action save() {
    this.#savedName = this.playerName; // commit snapshot
    this.args.onSave?.(this.playerName);
  }

  <template>
    <input value={{this.playerName}} {{on "input" this.update}} />
    <button disabled={{not this.isDirty}} {{on "click" this.save}}>Save</button>
  </template>
}
```
A boolean `isDirty` flag must be manually reset and can get out of sync — if the user types then deletes back to the original value, `isDirty` stays `true` even though nothing changed. Snapshot comparison derives `isDirty` as a getter, making it self-correcting: it is `false` whenever the current value matches the saved baseline, regardless of edit history. Use the snapshot approach for all forms where accuracy matters. The flag approach is only acceptable for irreversible operations (e.g., "has the user ever opened this panel").

```gjs
import Component from '@glimmer/component';
import { tracked } from '@glimmer/tracking';
import { action } from '@ember/object';

export default class ScoreEditorComponent extends Component {
  @tracked runs = 0;
  @tracked wickets = 0;

  // ✅ @action reset — for user-initiated "clear form" button
  @action
  reset() {
    this.runs = 0;
    this.wickets = 0;
  }

  // ✅ willDestroy — for cleanup side effects (timers, listeners), NOT for @tracked reset
  willDestroy() {
    super.willDestroy();
    // clearInterval, removeEventListener etc.
    // Do NOT reset @tracked here — component is already unmounting,
    // setting @tracked on a destroyed component throws an assertion
  }

  <template>
    <button {{on "click" this.reset}}>Reset</button>
    <p>{{this.runs}}/{{this.wickets}}</p>
  </template>
