  @action undo() {
    if (!this.canUndo) return;
    const prev = this.history.at(-1);
    this.history = this.history.slice(0, -1);
    this.score = prev;
  }

  <template>
    <p>{{this.score.runs}}/{{this.score.wickets}}</p>
    <button {{on "click" this.addRun}}>+Run</button>
    <button {{on "click" this.undo}} disabled={{not this.canUndo}}>Undo</button>
  </template>
}
```
Implement undo only when users make reversible edits where mistakes are costly (score corrections, lineup changes) and the undo operation is expected by the domain (cricket scoring tools routinely need score correction). The implementation is straightforward: before each mutation, push a snapshot of current state onto `@tracked history`; undo pops the last snapshot. Cap history length to prevent memory growth (`this.history.slice(-20)`). Skip undo for read-only displays, non-destructive additions, or actions with server-side confirmation dialogs.

