  @tracked isDark = localStorage.getItem('theme')
    ? localStorage.getItem('theme') === 'dark'
    : window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches;

  constructor(owner, args) {
    super(owner, args);
    // Listen for system preference changes
    window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)')
      .addEventListener('change', (e) => {
        if (!localStorage.getItem('theme')) { // only if no manual override
          this.isDark = e.matches;
        }
      });
    this.#applyTheme();
  }

  toggle() {
    this.isDark = !this.isDark;
    localStorage.setItem('theme', this.isDark ? 'dark' : 'light');
    this.#applyTheme();
  }

  #applyTheme() {
    document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark', this.isDark);
  }
}
```
Do both. Use `prefers-color-scheme` as the default to respect system preferences automatically — no user action required. Use `@tracked isDark` in a service so a manual toggle persists to `localStorage` and overrides the system default. React to system changes via `matchMedia.addEventListener` but only when no manual override exists. This three-tier priority (localStorage override > system preference > default light) is the industry-standard dark mode pattern.

