`@action` is a decorator that binds `this` for template event handler usage — it is not a general-purpose method annotation for internal logic. Calling one `@action` from another works but is semantically confusing because it implies the called method needs template binding, which it doesn't in that context. Extract shared internal logic into plain private methods (using the `#` prefix in ES2024) and keep `@action` only on methods wired to template events.

```gjs
